[1] Caribbean Islands
Date: Sun 18 Jul 2010
Source: Chicago Sun-Times [edited]
<http://www.suntimes.com/news/world/2507808,CST-NWS-fever18.article>


Dengue fever kills at least 33 in Caribbean
---------------------------------------------------
Mosquito-borne dengue fever is reaching epidemic stages across the
Caribbean. Dozens of deaths have been reported, and health
authorities are concerned it could get much worse as the rainy season
advances. The increase in cases is blamed on warm weather and an
unusually early rainy season, which has produced an explosion of
mosquitoes. Health officials say the flood of cases is straining the
region's hospitals.

In the Dominican Republic, where at least 27 deaths have been
reported, hundreds of health workers and soldiers went door-to-door
Saturday [17 Jul 2010] to warn about the virus and destroy mosquito
breeding areas.

Hospitals in Trinidad, where one death has been reported, are running
out of beds, and Puerto Rico is facing what officials say could be
its worst dengue outbreak in more than a decade.

"We are having a really large epidemic," said Kay Tomashek,
epidemiology section chief of the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention's dengue branch in Puerto Rico. At least 5 people have
died in the U.S. Caribbean territory, and 6300 suspected cases had
been reported as of mid-July. Only 100 more cases were reported
during the same period in 1998, the island's worst dengue outbreak.
By the end of that year, it had sickened 17 000 and killed 19.

Health officials fear the virus, which had once disappeared from the
United States, also could gain a foothold there. Test results for a
suspected case in the Miami area came back negative last week, but a
recent study found 5 percent of Key West residents show evidence they
had been exposed to the virus.

