[3] Puerto Rico
Date: Sat 17 Jul 2010
Source: BBC Mundo [in Spanish, trans. Corr.SB, edited]
<http://www.bbc.co.uk/mundo/america_latina/2010/07/100717_puerto_rico_dengue_lr.shtml>


The dengue epidemic in Puerto Rico, declared in February [2010], has
left 5 people dead so far this year. It has been worsened by the
rains, causing an increase of about 400 new cases reported per week,
according to official data. The government blames the rise to heavy
rains experienced by the country since May, and the presence of 3
different serotypes of the virus.

The latter, says U.S. Secretary of the Department of Health of Puerto
Rico, Lorenzo Gonzalez, means "we have more people susceptible to the
virus and it is likely that a given person can become infected on
more than one occasion [with a different virus serotype. - Mod.TY] in
the year."

The increase of cases occurred before the start of the dengue high
season in Puerto Rico, which is officially from August through
November.

On the other hand, Gonzalez noted the need to make the people aware
of the risk of disease, for which his department has requested
federal funds. "Contrary to the feeling of urgency that we saw in the
public to combat [influenza] H1N1, when citizens went to get
vaccinated and took personal supplies [of medications ?], we know
that has not been the same with dengue, he explained. In this
situation, the Department of Health has asked Puerto Ricans to "take
emergency measures to combat the epidemic." He reminded everyone that
the areas that tend to become breeding grounds for mosquitoes, are
the trash bins and, in general, any place where water is stored such
as unused plastic pools or watering containers for animals.

