[4] Trinidad and Tobago
Date: Sun 18 Jul 2010
Source: Trinidad and Tobago Newsday [edited]
<http://www.newsday.co.tt/news/0,124195.html>


At least one Princes Town resident was admitted suffering from the
dreaded dengue virus at the San Fernando General Hospital (SFGH) on
Friday [16 Jul 2010]. Speaking to Sunday Newsday from beneath his
mosquito-netted bed on Ward 15 yesterday, the patient, who lives at
St Julien Village, Princes Town, said a blood test taken at the
hospital on Friday morning [16 Jul 2010] had returned positive. The
man, who is employed at Claxton Bay said he started to feel unwell on
Tuesday evening [13 Jul 2010] and developed severe headaches, fever
and body pains and was taken to the hospital by relatives on Friday
morning. He was immediately placed on IV drips and admitted to Ward
15 where he was surrounded by 3 other men all lying under mosquito
nets.

Ag Medical Director, Dr Anand Chatoorgoon, in a telephone interview,
said he was unaware of any new cases of dengue fever at the hospital.

Meanwhile, in a statement, the SWRHA noted that several measures had
been put in place to deal with the overcrowding situation at the
hospital including the addition of 15 beds and the establishment of a
special dengue clinic at the Accident and Emergency department to
provide "daily follow up care for patient with symptoms who are
discharged."

The SWRHA also noted that "additional courier services have been
implemented between the hospital and supporting laboratories for
faster receipt of laboratory test results."

--
Communicated by:
HealthMap Alerts via ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The travel history of this patient is not given, so one does not
know if the dengue virus infection was locally acquired or imported
from another locale. The report does not mention the abundance and
distribution of the _Aedes aegypti_ dengue virus vector in the area
where the case occurred. If the infection was locally acquired and
the vector mosquito is abundant, as seems likely, the probability of
ongoing transmission there is significant.

The 15 Jul 2010 edition of Prensa Latina (in Spanish
<http://www.prensa-latina.cu/index.php?option=3Dcom_content&task=3Dview&id=3D205989&Itemid=3D1>)
reported that Health authorities in Trinidad and Tobago are now on
alert to the rapid spread of dengue in the country, as 2 deaths from
DHF have been reported and 242 people have been hospitalized from the
disease. According to the Health Minister, Therese Baptiste-Cornelis,
the Caribbean nation accounts for more than 400 confirmed cases since
late June 2010, when frequent rains caused rivers to overflow and
flooding occurred in several locations.

HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of the Caribbean area showing
the location of Trinidad & Tobago can be accessed at
<http://healthmap.org/promed/en?v=18.9,-70.5,5>. - Mod.TY]

