[8] Philippines (Zamboanga City)
Date: Sun 18 Jul 2010
Source: Business Mirror [edited]
<http://businessmirror.com.ph/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=27810:cholera-dengue-outbreak-reported-in-zamboanga-city&catid=45:regions&Itemid=71>


The City Health Office here has declared a "very high alert level"
due to the soaring cases of dengue in the city. Dr. Rodel Agbulos,
city health officer, said a total of 1052 dengue cases have been
recorded in this city from January - June this year [2010], with 9
fatalities, which already surpassed the total number of cases, and
fatalities, registered in 2009. This compares with the 1029 cases,
with 8 fatalities, for the entire 2009, he said.

"For the 1st week of July alone, we have registered 71 cases and when
we talk about deaths, a total of 9 cases were fatal from January to
the 1st week of this month [July 2010]," Agbulos said of the dengue
cases. "We are declaring a very high alert level," he added,
stressing that the number of registered cases has not reached the
outbreak level as of yet. He called on every resident of the city "to
do your share of helping prevent the spread of the mosquito-borne
disease [virus]." He said cleanliness in the surroundings and
sanitation are the most effective and no-cost prescriptions to dengue
fever.

City Health Office records showed that there were 156 cases of dengue
in January, 158 in February, 149 in March, 93 in April, 123 in May,
302 in June and 71 for the 1st week alone of July this year [2010].
Agbulos said barangay Campo Islam, a slum village west of this city,
registered the most number of dengue fever cases since the 1st month
of this year.

Zamboanga City experienced an outbreak of dengue fever in 2007, when
cases of dengue soared to more than 3000 and Agbulos warned that if
nothing will be done, the present situation might reach the same
level as 3 years ago.

[Byline: Bong Garcia Jr.]

